doc.ContractDescription: VARIATIONS IN THE SALINITY OF THE OCEAN ARE PRODUCED BY EVAPORATION, PRECIPITATION AND RUNOFF AT THE OCEAN SURFACE. THIS SALINITY VARIANCE INTRODUCED AT THE SURFACE IS DISSIPATED BY INTERNAL OCEAN MIXING PROCESSES. IT WILL SOON BE POSSIBLE TO MAKE CREDIBLE ESTIMATES OF THE SURFACE PRODUCTION OF SALINITY VARIANCE BY USING NEW ESTIMATES OF EVAPORATION - PRECIPITATION BY SCHANZE, SCHMITT AND YU (2010) AND THE SURFACE SALINITY FIELDS PRODUCED BY AQUARIUS. THE GLOBAL SURFACE INTEGRAL OF SALINITY TIMES ITS FLUX CAN BE SHOWN TO BE RELATED TO THE VOLUME INTEGRAL OF DISSIPATION OF SALINITY VARIANCE BY MIXING (STERN, 1975). HOWEVER, ONLY ROUGH ESTIMATES OF SUCH QUANTITIES HAVE BEEN MADE IN THE PAST AND THESE NEW SALINITY AND FLUX DATA SETS WILL ALLOW A MUCH MORE QUANTITATIVE EVALUATION OF THE PRODUCTION OF SALINITY VARIANCE. THE DISSIPATION OF SALINITY VARIANCE WILL BE EXAMINED USING OUR UNDERSTANDING OF OCEAN MIXING PROCESSES AND THEIR RELATIONSHIP TO WATER MASS STRUCTURE AND STRATIFICATION PARAMETERS SUCH AS THE DENSITY RATIO. THE GOAL IS TO IDENTIFY THE REGIONS AND DENSITY STRATA WHERE INTERNAL MIXING APPEARS TO BE MOST IMPORTANT AND PUT CONSTRAINTS ON ITS MAGNITUDE. UNDERSTANDING THE RESPONSE OF THE OCEAN TO SALINITY FORCING IS KEY TO PROPER APPRECIATION OF THE EFFECTS OF THE WATER CYCLE ON THE OCEAN. SINCE THE OCEAN CANNOT CREATE SALINITY VARIANCE ON ITS OWN, THE RECENTLY IDENTIFIED INCREASE IN SURFACE SALINITY VARIANCE IS OF GREAT INTEREST AS BEING AN INDICATOR OF A CHANGING GLOBAL WATER CYCLE (DURACK AND WIJFFELS, 2010). SINCE MOST OF THE WATER CYCLE IS OVER THE OCEAN, IT IS LOGICAL THAT THE OCEAN SALINITY FIELD SHOULD PROVIDE THE MOST ROBUST ESTIMATES OF CHANGE IN THE WATER CYCLE. IN THIS STUDY, THE MAGNITUDE OF SALINITY VARIANCE GENERATION, ITS RELATION TO OCEAN MIXING PROCESSES, AND ITS POTENTIAL FOR INFORMING US ABOUT THE MAGNITUDE OF CHANGE IN THE GLOBAL WATER CYCLE WILL BE DESCRIBED AND DOCUMENTED USING THE RAPIDLY IMPROVING SALINITY DATA SETS EMERGING FROM ARGO AND AQUARIUS.

VISN 1 REAL TIME LOCATION SYSTEM FOR VISN 1_SHORT-TERM POP EXTENSION

WE REQUEST NASA ADAP SUPPORT TO INFER THE EVOLUTIONARY STATE, LUMINOSITIES, AND MASSES OF 3,000 STAR-FORMING DENSE MOLECULAR CORES USING HERSCHEL HI-GAL DATA. THE TARGET CORES ARE SELECTED FROM THE 870 M ATLASGAL SURVEY TO HOST THE EARLY STAGES OF HIGH-MASS STAR FORMATION AND TO SPAN THE COMPLETE RANGE OF THEIR EARLY EVOLUTIONARY STAGES. ALL 3,000 OF THESE CORES WILL BE MAPPED IN THE MILLIMETER ASTRONOMY LEGACY TEAM 90 GHZ SURVEY (MALT90), A NEW PROJECT DESIGNED TO SIMULTANEOUSLY IMAGE 16 MOLECULAR LINES NEAR 90 GHZ. THE DUST TEMPERATURES DERIVED FROM THE HI-GAL DATA WILL PROVIDE THE KEY DIAGNOSTIC OF THE EVOLUTIONARY PHASE, AS THE CORES EVOLVE DUE TO HEATING BY THE EMBEDDED YOUNG STARS FROM THE EARLIEST COLD STARLESS CORES, TO INTERMEDIATE TEMPERATURE PROTOSTELLAR CORES, AND FINALLY ON TO HOT CORES AND H II REGIONS. WE WILL CORRELATE THE EVOLUTIONARY STATE INDICATED BY THE HI-GAL DUST TEMPERATURES WITH THE CHEMICAL AND KINEMATIC INFORMATION SUPPLIED BY THE MALT 90 MOLECULAR LINE SURVEY. MOREOVER, SINCE MALT 90 DATA PROVIDES KINEMATIC DISTANCES, THE HI-GAL SUBMM/FIR SPECTRAL ENERGY DISTRIBUTIONS WILL ALSO PROVIDE THE LUMINOSITY AND MASS DISTRIBUTIONS OF DENSE CORES. THIS PROJECT WILL ALLOW FOR THE FIRST TIME A COMPLETE AND ROBUST CHARACTERIZATION OF THE PHYSICAL EVOLUTION OF DENSE CORES. SINCE THIS PROJECT STUDIES THE FORMATION OF HIGH-MASS STARS, IT BEARS DIRECTLY ON NASA'S ORIGINS THEME.
